{
  "doc_id": "2188",
  "text": "The ultimate evidence for phosphorylation consists of identification of the phosphorylated amino acid residue(s) in a protein sequence. In thylakoids the phosphorylation sites have been revealed in the PSII polypeptides D1, D2, CP43, and PsbH (20 -22) , in four subunits of the major LHCII complex [CITATION_1] , in the minor chlorophyll a/b protein CP29 [CITATION_2] , and in thylakoid-soluble phosphoprotein of 9 kDa (TSP9) with yet unknown function [CITATION_3] . All of these proteins were found to be phosphorylated at threonine residues with the only exception being one LHCII polypeptide from spinach phosphorylated at a serine residue [CITATION_4] . Two distinct phosphorylation sites were found in PsbH [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , and three were found in TSP9 [CITATION_7] . TSP9 is uniquely released from the membranes after the light-induced phosphorylation that could probably serve in the cell signaling [CITATION_8] . All other identified thylakoid phosphoproteins are integral membrane polypeptides with their phosphorylation sites exposed to the outer surface of thylakoids. Notably, the phosphorylated peptides could be \"shaved\" from the surface of thylakoids by trypsin [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Analysis of the released peptide mixtures by liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry allows for simultaneous determination of phosphorylation states for multiple membrane proteins by measuring the ratios of phosphopeptide to dephosphopeptide from each of them [CITATION_11] . This approach has revealed the levels of in vivo phosphorylation for four PSII proteins in thylakoid membranes from the leaves of Arabidopsis thaliana exposed to a subset of different physiological conditions [CITATION_12] . The liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry provides an unprecedented tool for unraveling the dynamic protein phosphorylation network in vivo. However, these analyses could be accomplished only for the proteins with the localized phosphorylation positions. Thus, comprehensive studies on phosphorylation in the photosynthetic membranes require identification of all natural phosphorylation sites in thylakoid proteins.",
